annotation.TEXT: The first usage of this oft-repeated phrase by our riffers.
“Helter Skelter” is a song by the Beatles on the so-called White Album, released in 1968.
One of the oldest running gags on the show, dating back to KTMA. According to Trace Beaulieu, Crow simplified the entire animal kingdom into either “doggies” or “kitties.”
In 1989, a planned retrospective of Mapplethorpe’s work at a D.C. museum was canceled after conservatives kicked up a ruckus over his “pornographic” photos.
Aviation Week & Space Technology, often called Aviation Week, is a weekly periodical covering the aerospace industry, first published in 1916.
“On Top of Old Smoky” is a folk song dating back to the 1800s and likely is about a mountain in the Ozarks. The Weavers recorded a hit version in 1951.
“It’s a madhouse! A madhouse!” is a line from the film Planet of the Apes.
The use of the rimshot or sting at the punchline of a joke dates back to early 20th-century vaudeville performers.
These were the names of kids on Leave It to Beaver.
Twister was controversial when it was introduced in the mid-‘60s; its company, Milton Bradley, was accused of selling “sex in a box.”
In Olympic event scoring, Russian judges are often considered to be especially strict.
Amusingly, Field’s actual screenwriting credits are few, but his fingerprints are all over Hollywood to this day.
Solitaire can refer to any card game played by one person. In the U.K., one-person card games are called Patience.
Sid Vicious was the bass player for the Sex Pistols. He and his girlfriend, Nancy Spungen, abused heroin and other drugs. She was stabbed to death and he was charged, but O.D.’d before the trial.
Adolf Hitler was also an animal lover, particularly of dogs. His favorite was a German shepherd named Blondi (of course).
Better films Cesar Romero appeared in include The Thin Man, Ocean’s 11, and, of course, Batman: The Movie.
Leave It to Beaver ran from 1957-63 and has become the epitome of the wholesome family sitcom.
Operation is a classic board game in which players use tweezers to remove “organs” from the “patient.” Brush the sensors and a buzzer sounds, ending your turn.
Mutual of Omaha is a Nebraska insurance company best known for sponsoring the nature show Wild Kingdom from 1963-1988 and its revival, which began airing in 2002.
The punch line of a joke about a drunk looking for his keys under a streetlight. A passerby asks if they were lost there, and the drunk replies, “No, but the light is so much better here.”
Triceratops (meaning “three-horned face”) is one of the best-known dinosaurs ever discovered. It was first found in 1887 and dates back some 68 million years.
Quoting Sir John Gielgud from the movie Arthur.
Let us know if we missed any references!
A reference to the 1970 film When Dinosaurs Ruled the Earth, which featured stop-motion beasts and Playboy Playmate Victoria Vetri.
In the film Raiders of the Lost Ark, there is a famous sequence in which Indiana Jones chases after a truck full of Nazi soldiers with all kinds of action and stunts.
Marcel Marceau was a famous French mime—just about the only one society could tolerate.
Lippy the Lion and Hardy Har Har were Hanna-Barbera cartoon characters: a lion in a top hat and a depressed hyena, respectively.
The ionosphere is part of the upper atmosphere, extending from about 50 miles up to 600 miles above the Earth’s surface.
When asked why he wanted to scale Mt. Everest, British climber George Leigh Mallory responded, “Because it’s there.” Mallory died on the mountain the following year.
There’s a Bowling Green in Kentucky, Ohio, Missouri, and Virginia, but not in Tennessee, although it does have a Bowling Green Cemetery. It looks like a pleasant place to be dead.
The arcade version of Pong appeared in 1972; the home version in 1975.
Droopy was a take on Wallace Wimple, a character on the popular radio show Fibber McGee and Molly; Bill Thompson, who voiced Droopy, also played Wimple.
In the film The Wizard of Oz, Dorothy’s farmhouse is lifted by a tornado and lands on the Wicked Witch of the East. The film begins in sepia-toned Kansas; in Oz it transitions to color.
We hope you enjoyed the fully-annotated Lost Continent.
Sloe gin fizz is a cocktail made with sloe gin, lemon juice, sugar, club soda, and sometimes egg white.
Mannix was a star football and basketball player, a black belt in karate, and skilled at many other sports, such as skiing, riding, sailing, and golf.
Jays Foods is a maker of snacks in Chicago; products include potato chips and popcorn. It was acquired by Snyder’s of Hanover in 2007.
Yes. This stock footage was also used in Episode 107, Robot Monster, and Episode 201, Rocketship X-M.
A party ball is a small, round keg of beer. Coors made them for about 30 years.
An imitation of Jerry Lewis. One of his best-known shticks was lapsing into the voice and mannerisms of a twitchy, geeky, and semi-moronic man-child.
Duran Duran is a British New Wave group most popular in the ‘80s. Hits include “Girls on Film,” “Rio,” and “Hungry Like the Wolf.”
Sir Edmund Hillary and his guide, Tenzing Norgay, were the first climbers to reach the summit of Mount Everest.
The Loma Prieta Earthquake hit San Francisco on Oct. 17, 1989, measuring 6.9 on the Richter scale. Sixty-three people were killed and nearly 4,000 were injured.
An imitation of Roseanne Roseannadanna, a character played by Gilda Radner on the Weekend Update segment of SNL. One of her catchphrases was “If it ain’t one thing, it’s another!”
Richard Gere’s desperate words to Lou Gossett Jr. in the film An Officer and a Gentleman when Gossett threatens to throw him out of Officer Candidate School.
And stay tuned after the movie for a clip from a recent MST3K Turkey Day Marathon.
Businessman Henry Phillips and engineer John Thompson developed the Phillips screw. The plus-sign shape on the screw’s head keeps the screwdriver centered and the screw straight.
Beyond the short-lived TV series (1964-67), the Gilligan’s Island saga continued into three TV movies and two animated series.
Part of the usual spiel flight attendants give airplane passengers before takeoff.
Hunt-Wesson is an older name for food producer Hunt’s that was coined after they merged with Wesson Oil. They’re all part of ConAgra Foods now.
A reference to Episode 207, Wild Rebels.
“Forever Young” was the title of a 1974 song by Bob Dylan and a 1988 song by Rod Stewart.
Theodore “The Beaver” Cleaver was Ward’s younger son on the sitcom Leave It to Beaver.
Actress/writer Mae West was a sex symbol and an unparalleled spouter of double entendres.
If we missed any, let us know in the comments!
A callback to Episode 201, Rocketship X-M.
On Leave It to Beaver, the Cleaver children were “The Beaver” (Jerry Mathers) and Wally (Tony Dow).
“Nobody But Me” is a 1962 Isley Brothers song that was covered by The Human Beinz in 1967. In just 2 minutes and 16 seconds, it says the word “no” more than 100 times.
Learn the meaning behind all the references in the film. Yes, all of them.
Tab is a saccharin-based diet cola made by Coca-Cola; Coke switched its efforts to Diet Coke after unfavorable lab studies of saccharin in the early ‘80s.
The ads for Alfred Hitchcock’s horror classic Psycho used the slogan “No one … BUT NO ONE … will be admitted to the theatre after the start of each performance.”
In the Marx Brothers film Animal Crackers, Groucho dictates a letter to his lawyer, Charles H. Hungerdunger, of Hungerdunger, Hungerdunger, Hungerdunger, Hungerdunger, and McCormick.
Cesar Romero refused to shave his trademark moustache when playing the Joker, so white makeup was slathered unconvincingly on top of it.
Lost Continent: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Mel Tormé, aka the “Velvet Fog,” was one of the 20th century’s most respected jazz vocalists.
Aaron Copland was an American composer known for his ballet Rodeo (“Beef. It’s what’s for dinner”) and Fanfare for the Common Man (frequently used at sporting events).
Lewis went on to star solo in hits like The Bellboy, The Ladies Man, and The Nutty Professor.
The riff is a paraphrase of a saying attributed to Jesus in the New Testament: “Render unto Caesar the things which are Caesar’s, and unto God the things that are God’s.”
A couple of typical phrases uttered by Moe Howard, leader of the Three Stooges.
The “gasp” line of an old campfire story.
Igor Stravinsky was a Russian modernist composer; his Rite of Spring caused a near-riot when it premiered.
The Manhattan is a cocktail that originated in New York City in the late 19th century; it’s made with whiskey, sweet red vermouth, bitters, and a cherry.
And stick around for a clip from a recent MST3K Turkey Day Marathon.
An “mR” is a milliroentgen, one-thousandth of a roentgen, an obsolete unit for measuring the amount of radiation exposure, as in medical X-rays.
Shoah (Hebrew for “Holocaust”) is a 10-hour French documentary about the persecution and attempted genocide of the Jews by Nazi Germany.
On Gilligan’s Island, The Skipper (Alan Hale Jr.) called Gilligan (Bob Denver) “li’l buddy”.
Quoting C-3PO from Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope.
An imitation of Shaggy, a scruffy, goateed character on the Scooby-Doo animated TV series. He was voiced by Casey Kasem, the well-known syndicated DJ.
This phrase used in hide and seek comes either from the German “Alle, alle auch sind frei” (“everyone, everyone is also free”) or “All ye, all ye ‘outs’ in free.”
A line from the song “High Hopes,” written by Jimmy Van Heusen and Sammy Cahn and sung by Frank Sinatra in the 1959 film A Hole in the Head.
Battleship Potemkin is a classic Russian silent film directed by Sergei Eisenstein. The most famous scene is the Odessa Steps sequence, which shows a massacre of civilians.
Lines from the Star Trek episode “The Savage Curtain.”
A reference to Episode 203, Jungle Goddess.
Another reference to Bela Lugosi in the Phantom Creeps short in Episode 203, Jungle Goddess.
AC and DC can refer to different ways of transmitting electricity (alternating or direct current); “AC/DC” is also slang for bisexual.
“Nyuk, nyuk, nyuk” was one of Curly Howard’s trademark vocalizations in the Three Stooges shorts.
Will Rogers was a folksy actor, humorist, and social commentator known for his vaudeville act as a trick roper.
The Three Mile Island nuclear power plant in Pennsylvania suffered a partial meltdown in 1979. 140,000 people were evacuated, and the plant was closed forever.
If we missed any reference, be sure to let us know in the comments!
George’s wife Jane was voiced by Penny Singleton, best known for playing Blondie Bumstead on the radio and in a lengthy series of films.
Actor Sid Melton played Uncle Charlie Halper on the sitcom Make Room for Daddy (aka The Danny Thomas Show).
“Take my wife—please” was comedian Henny Youngman’s most famous joke, although he adored his wife, Sadie, to whom he was married for more than 60 years.
A paraphrased line from the film Monty Python’s The Meaning of Life, from a scene in which a British soldier has had his leg bitten off by a wild animal.
References to Episodes 103, 203, and 201, respectively. The Mad Monster was also directed by Sam Newfield.
“Climb Ev’ry Mountain” is a song from the Rodgers and Hammerstein musical The Sound of Music.
In her later life, actress Katharine Hepburn suffered from “essential tremor”: her head and hands shook constantly and a quaver affected her voice.
Dean Martin had a successful yet contentious partnership with Jerry Lewis in the 1940s and ‘50s and then a lengthy movie and music career on his own.
A paraphrase of the exchange between Indiana Jones and his treacherous guide, Satipo, at the beginning of Raiders of the Lost Ark.
Hogan’s Heroes was a sitcom about Allied soldiers in a German POW camp (Stalag 13) during WWII. The POWs’ leader was Col. Robert Hogan, played by Bob Crane.
Ward Cleaver’s work remained carefully unspecified on Leave It to Beaver. He carried a briefcase and worked in a nice office for a big company; good enough.
Maalox is a brand of OTC antacids first sold in 1949.
Polychlorinates are used in plastics and solvents (as in, polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs).
Jerry Lewis is a comedian who rose to fame with Dean Martin and then did a string of his own films.
Carlos Castaneda was a Peruvian-American author whose first book, The Teachings of Don Juan, detailed his years with a Yaqui shaman, Don Juan Matus. Its veracity has been questioned.
German physicist Hans Geiger and Ernest Rutherford invented the Geiger counter in 1908 to detect alpha rays. In 1928, an improved version, the Geiger-Müller counter, was introduced.
Dunlop Rubber was a U.K. tire producer. Composer Paul Dunlap scored other MSTied films, including The Rebel Set and I Was a Teenage Werewolf.
This is the classic exclamation uttered by Homer Simpson on the TV show The Simpsons. Twenty years before that, it was used by the Skipper on Gilligan’s Island.
In the movie The Great Escape, POWs digging escape tunnels dispose of the dirt by way of their pant legs.
Harvard University is one of the oldest and most prestigious universities in the United States, founded in 1636.
“Turd Museum” is an old Steve Martin joke: “I went to the turd museum today. They’ve got some great shit there. You know, some of that crap is worth a lot of money.”
Cagney’s character was based on a real-life criminal, Francis "Two-Gun" Crowley, who was arrested in New York in 1931 after a two-hour gun battle with police.
Executive producer Robert Lippert produced many films, including Episode 520, Radar Secret Service, and directed Episode 611, Last of the Wild Horses.
Paul Gauguin was a French Post-Impressionist painter who lived in Tahiti for years, painting a lot of pictures of topless women.
Mike Connors (under the name “Touch Connors”) appeared in Episode 503, Swamp Diamonds.
Lucite is one of several brand names for the transparent plastic material polymethyl methacrylate. Another well-known brand name is Plexiglas.
In Close Encounters of the Third Kind, Roy Neary (played by Richard Dreyfuss) sculpts a tower out of mashed potatoes at the dinner table.
“Si” means “yes” in more than a dozen languages, including Spanish and Italian.
“Meanwhile …” may have started in silent film, but once the talkies came in, the phrase was still used by narrators for films and radio and TV shows.
In the (in)famous TV ads for LifeCall, which made small devices the elderly could use to notify medical services, “Mrs. Fletcher” said, “I’ve fallen, and I can’t get up!”
This is the end to a famous campfire tale wherein a hook-handed maniac terrorizes teens making out in cars.
It consists of chicken or turkey, bacon, hard-boiled egg, tomatoes, avocado, scallions, watercress, chopped lettuce, blue cheese, and a vinaigrette dressing.
The 1990 Northwest Airlines flight mentioned earlier was from Fargo, North Dakota, to Minneapolis, Minnesota.
Albert Camus was a French philosopher and writer known for absurdism. Major works include The Stranger, The Plague, and The Myth of Sisyphus.
Martin Landau is known for playing IMF agent Rollin Hand on Mission: Impossible. Richard Landau was a TV and film writer. They are not brothers.
Shake-A-Pudd’n was a brand of instant pudding sold in a cup. Just add water and shake.
Director Ridley Scott is best known for the sci-fi classics Alien and Blade Runner. Both films were pretty foggy.
The German idealist philosophical movement of the 19th century (which included Friedrich Schelling and Georg Hegel) debated the perception of existence.
A reference to an old ad jingle for Dairy Queen restaurants: “In the land of Dairy Queen, we treat you right!” The ads showed close-ups of sundae toppings looking like mountains.
This phrase originated with title cards used in silent films; in westerns, it was often “Meanwhile, back at the ranch ...”
Sinatra recorded another version of the song for his friend John F. Kennedy, who used it as the theme song for his successful 1960 presidential campaign.
Sabu Dastagir was an Indian actor often credited only as Sabu. He became well known in the ‘40s; films included The Thief of Bagdad, Jungle Book, and Arabian Nights.
A line from Warren Zevon’s 1978 hit song “Werewolves of London.”
Gilligan’s Island was a sitcom about a group of people stranded on an island. Gilligan was the S.S. Minnow’s first mate. Mary Ann Summers was a farm girl who baked pies, somehow.
“Say uncle” is a demand for submission, usually by schoolyard bullies. The earliest published example of the phrase dates to a joke in the late 1800s.
Don Knotts starred in The Incredible Mr. Limpet as a bookkeeper who is transformed into a cartoon fish. Robert Lippert produced many films, including several MST3K episodes.
An imitation of one Ted Baxter (played by Ted Knight), anchorman on WJM-TV, as depicted on the sitcom The Mary Tyler Moore Show.
AM radio was developed by Reginald Fessenden, while FM radio was developed several decades later by Edwin Armstrong.
Mattress tag warnings are directed at the manufacturers and retailers, to prevent them from passing off old mattresses as new ones, as they had in the past.
Austrian-born Adolf Hitler was the chancellor and Führer of Germany before and during WWII.
A reference to ads for Fisher Nuts, founded in 1920 in St. Paul, Minnesota, by Russian immigrant Sam Fisher.
Amazingly, all three disgraced pilots eventually returned to the commercial airline industry, either as pilots or instructors or both.
Actor Henry Fonda was known for roles in The Grapes of Wrath, 12 Angry Men, The Longest Day, and On Golden Pond.
Pee-wee’s Playhouse was a Saturday morning kids’ show that starred Paul Reubens as the titular man-child, Pee-wee Herman.
Stuckey’s is a chain of roadside restaurants/souvenir shops that at one time littered America’s highways. You can still buy the occasional Pecan Log in the South or Southeast.
On Gilligan’s Island, Roy Hinkley (Russell Johnson) was a high school science teacher nicknamed the “Professor”; he specialized in making contraptions out of coconuts and bamboo.
Photographer Robert Mapplethorpe’s most controversial work was his shots of the underground BDSM and bondage scene in New York City.
Mount Rushmore in South Dakota features the gigantic carved heads of four presidents: Washington, Jefferson, Lincoln, and Teddy Roosevelt. The work took 14 years to complete.
Lee Press-On Nails were a brand of artificial women’s fingernails popular in the ‘80s.
In 1846 a scholar converted the trade goods the Dutch paid for Manhattan to $24; ever since people have been failing to account for inflation. Both sides seem to have thought the deal was fair.
In the closing credits of The Jetsons, George Jetson yells this to his wife as their dog drags him into a high-speed chase on a treadmill, intent on catching a cat.
A reference to the famous line “Shaking it up here, boss!” from the film Cool Hand Luke, starring Paul Newman as a loner on a chain gang.
The Book of Revelation is the final book of the New Testament, written by one John of Patmos around 95 C.E.
“Jimmy” in this case being a slang term for “penis” and the condom being a “hat” for it.
Droopy is a cartoon dog with a slow, deadpan delivery that appeared in 24 theatrical shorts from 1943-58.
No one was hurt in the incident, but the pilots were all fired, had their licenses revoked, and served time in federal prison.
Actress Hillary Brooke played Lou Costello’s (not Bud Abbott’s) love interest on The Abbott and Costello Show on TV and appeared in a couple of their films.
In the Vietnam War film Platoon, Lieutenant Wolfe orders his soldiers to burn a village suspected of aiding the North Vietnamese guerrillas.
After a plane crash in the Andes Mountains in 1972, members of a Uruguayan rugby team were forced to eat the bodies of the victims to stay alive.
The B-52s are a pop-new wave band (with retro flair) founded in 1976. “Rock Lobster” was their first single.
While AM radio can have greater range than FM, FM has the capacity for greater sound quality. That’s why most music stations are on the FM side of the dial.
June Cleaver was Ward’s wife on Leave It to Beaver. She was played by Barbara Billingsley.
Dinty Moore is a brand of canned beef stew first manufactured by Hormel in 1935.
A paraphrased line from Act III, Scene II of William Shakespeare’s Julius Caesar.
“Jimmy hat” is a slang term for a condom.
“Purple Haze” is a classic psychedelic song by Jimi Hendrix.
The actress Acquanetta was promoted as South American, getting roles as an exotic beauty. She was actually born in Wyoming of either Native American or African-American descent.
A paraphrase of the famous line in Jaws: “You’re gonna need a bigger boat.”
Nightclub comedian Morty Gunty appeared on many TV shows from the ‘50s to the ‘70s and acted in a couple of feature films.
The dog George Jetson was walking on the treadmill, Astro, was voiced by Don Messick, who also voiced Scooby-Doo.
“Rock the Casbah” is a 1982 hit single by English punk band The Clash.
Writer/director George Romero is considered the master of the zombie film; his movies include Night of the Living Dead and Dawn of the Dead.
A paraphrase of one of Fonda’s famous lines from The Grapes of Wrath.
In an SNL Untouchables skit, Dan Aykroyd, as Eliot Ness, called, “Lee! Rico! Youngblood!” (The character on the show was “Youngfellow.”) The Frank Zappa song “The Untouchables” made the same error.
The Catskill Mountains in New York served as a getaway for vacationers from New York City. It became the training ground for standup comics in the early and mid-20th century.
The White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico is a military testing range used to test nuclear weapons as well as rockets and vehicles for the space program.
Krakatoa, East of Java is a film about the catastrophic 1883 eruption of the volcano Krakatoa. Krakatoa is in fact located west of the island of Java.
A line spoken by Bela Lugosi in the Phantom Creeps short in Episode 203, Jungle Goddess.
“Mano a mano” is a Spanish phrase meaning “hand to hand.” It was first used for bullfights in which two matadors competed for the audience’s love.
A paraphrase of the classic line from the Jimmy Cagney film White Heat: “Made it, Ma! Top of the world!”
Germany invaded Poland in September 1939, setting off WWII. They did so after a false flag operation, when Nazis disguised as Poles attacked a German radio station (the Gleiwitz incident).
King Arthur screamed “Run away!” in the comedy Monty Python and the Holy Grail as the French hurled cows and other animals at his knights.
Dean Martin had a successful yet contentious partnership with Jerry Lewis in the 1940s and ‘50s and then a lengthy movie and music career on his own.
Ames is a city in central Iowa; population about 60,000. It is home to the famous Ames Straw Poll, seen as a barometer for aspiring Republican presidential candidates.
“Snot running down his nose” is a line from the Jethro Tull song “Aqualung.”
Satipo was Molina’s first film role; in a 2013 interview he called it a “gift from God.”
In the ‘60s TV series Batman, whenever Batman and Robin had to scale a building via Batrope, this was achieved by filming the actors walking horizontally and turning the image sideways.
A callback to Episode 202, Sidehackers.
“Jeepers” is a minced oath (subbing for “Jesus”). It first appeared in the 1920s.
Pong was one of the first video games. It was essentially an electronic version of table tennis: each player had a “paddle,” and they bounced a little “ball” between them.
The Nobel Prize is awarded every year in chemistry, physics, physiology/medicine, literature, and peace. Sweden’s central bank later created an economics prize as well.
Vitalis is a line of men’s hair-care products.
Another paraphrased line from Planet of the Apes.
A paraphrased line from Stanley Kubrick’s sci-fi classic 2001: A Space Odyssey, spoken by the computer HAL 9000.
A famous line from the film The Elephant Man: “I am not an elephant! I am not an animal! I am a human being! I ... am ... a ... man!”
Comedian George O’Hanlon supplied the voice of George Jetson.
“It doesn’t get any better than this” was a longtime ad slogan for Old Milwaukee beer.
The theremin is an electronic musical instrument that is played without ever being touched. It produces an eerie sound that meshed well with ‘50s sci-fi films.
Bikini Atoll is a small atoll in the Pacific. After WWII, the U.S. used it to test nuclear bombs, relocating its inhabitants to a nearby atoll, where they nearly starved to death.
Perkins Restaurant and Bakery is a casual dining chain offering breakfast any time and selling fresh-baked pastries.
Some of Martin and Lewis’s hit films included Scared Stiff, Hollywood or Bust, and The Caddy.
When playing Twister, players place their hands and feet on different colored circles until they’re all hopelessly tangled and fall into a gigantic heap.
Colitis is an inflammation of the large intestine that can be acute or chronic and has several possible causes (infection, complications from surgery, chemical irritation, etc.).
“The Pink Panther Theme” was written by Henry Mancini for the film The Pink Panther. It has been used for many films and TV shows since then.
Droopy’s lugubrious voice was supplied by several actors, including Bill Thompson, Don Messick, and animator Tex Avery.
“Don’t worry, honey, it’s just God bowling” (or “the angels bowling”) is sometimes used by parents to reassure frightened children during a thunderstorm.
Chippendales is a dance troupe of male strippers aimed at a female audience. They have spawned a successful merchandising line that includes calendars, playing cards, etc.
The original Star Trek series followed the adventures of Captain Kirk, Mr. Spock, and the rest of the crew aboard the USS Enterprise.
A paraphrased line from the sci-fi movie Dune.
“Tail-Gunner Joe” was the nickname of commie-hating demagogue Senator Joseph McCarthy, from his false claim that he was a bomber tail-gunner in WWII.
Actor George Kennedy played airline mechanic Joe Patroni in the disaster flick Airport and reprised the role in all three sequels.
For more than a century, scientists thought calling the Brontosaurus a separate species of dinosaur was a mistake. In 2015, they announced it is, in fact, distinct from the Apatosaurus.
In the final days of WWII, scientists who worked on the V-2 (including Wernher von Braun) surrendered to the U.S. They helped develop the rockets that powered the space program.
Sometimes referred to as “sad trombone” or, more technically, “chromatic descending ‘wah,’” this sound effect dates back to early 1900s vaudeville.
The double bass (aka string bass or contrabass) is a large stringed musical instrument originating in the 1400s and still played in orchestras and jazz groups.
In diner lingo, “Adam and Eve on a raft” means two poached eggs on toast. (“Adam and Eve on a raft and wreck ‘em” means two scrambled eggs on toast.)
Section 8 was a military discharge given to mentally unfit soldiers. Corporal Klinger wore dresses on M*A*S*H because he hoped to be sent home under a Section 8.
Robert Ryan was a tough guy actor who appeared in such films as The Dirty Dozen, The Wild Bunch, and The Longest Day.
“Love on the Rocks” is a Neil Diamond song that was used in the film The Jazz Singer.
Bloomingdale’s is a high-end department store that was started as a hoop-skirt store by Joseph and Lyman Bloomingdale in 1861 in New York City.
In Episode 207, Wild Rebels, Citrusville was the site of the film’s climax.
Mannix was a TV series starring Mike Connors as Joe Mannix, a P.I. in Los Angeles who indulged in frequent car chases, shootouts, and fistfights.
“Stuck in the Middle with You” is a 1972 hit single by Stealers Wheel.
June Cleaver was known for always being dressed to the nines: an elegant dress, heels, and a pearl necklace even while vacuuming the house or gardening.
Now for your viewing pleasure…the fully annotated Lost Continent!
Cesar Romero was best known for portraying Latin lovers and men of action until he played the Joker on the ‘60s Batman TV show.
Dinah Shore was a singer, actress, and TV personality who hosted two daytime talk shows in the ‘70s and a third from 1989-92.
Hugh Beaumont was best known for playing all-knowing father Ward Cleaver on Leave It to Beaver.
The Wackiest Ship in the Army is a film about a lieutenant who takes command of a ship full of misfits during WWII. There was also a short-lived TV series by the same name.
Eleanor Roosevelt was the wife of President Franklin Roosevelt and First Lady from 1933-45. While she was an accomplished, intelligent woman, she was not conventionally attractive.
NY-born Brothers Sam Newfield and Sigmund Neufeld worked together constantly. Sam used pseudonyms to hide the fact that he directed so many of the company’s films.
Respected actor Robert Mitchum was known for film noir movies like Cape Fear, The Night of the Hunter, and Crossfire.
An imitation of Theodore “Beaver” Cleaver. The character was based on writer Joe Connelly’s son Ricky.
Another character from Leave It to Beaver; a friend of Beaver, Larry Mondello was played by Robert “Rusty” Stevens.
Chick Chandler was a longtime character actor. He’s best known to MSTies as the incompetent angel Wilbur in the short “Once Upon a Honeymoon.”
The Donner Party was a group of settlers who were trapped in the Sierra Nevadas in the winter of 1846; nearly half of them died, and the party turned to cannibalism to survive.
In the ‘40s and ’50s Vitalis tonic was used to slick the hair back in a socially conservative fashion.
“Bungle in the Jungle” is a song by the British prog rock band Jethro Tull, from their album War Child.
Another line from Batman, this one spoken by Jack Nicholson as the Joker.
Actor Doug McClure starred in the sci-fi films The Land That Time Forgot and The People That Time Forgot.
Midway is a star-studded film about the Battle of Midway in WWII. It was released in Sensurround, which used low-frequency sounds to create rumbling sensations.
The Grateful Dead was a famed rock band from the heyday of the ‘60s, though they remained active until lead singer Jerry Garcia’s death in 1995.
A paraphrase of the opening voiceover by Martin Sheen in the film Apocalypse Now.
In 1990 3 pilots for Northwest Airlines were arrested in Minneapolis for flying drunk; the captain had drunk 15 rum and diet colas the night before the flight.
A line spoken by Michael Keaton in the title role of the 1989 Tim Burton film Batman.
The Gods Must Be Crazy is a South African comedy film about a tribesman from Botswana who finds an empty Coke bottle and concludes it is a present from the gods.
“ASAP” is an initialism/acronym for “as soon as possible.”
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Danny Noonan was played by Michael O’Keefe, who went on to play Roseanne’s brother-in-law on Roseanne.
The Mountain Time Zone is two hours behind the Eastern Time Zone. States in the zone include Arizona, New Mexico, Colorado, Montana, Wyoming, and Utah.
Syd Field taught screenwriting at USC and wrote several books on screenwriting that are considered the gold standard in Hollywood.
Twinkies are a yellow, cream-filled snack cake invented by James Dewar in 1930. The filling was banana-flavored until WWII.

In the film Caddyshack, when Danny Noonan is trying to sink a putt, his fellow caddies try to distract him from the sidelines by chanting his name.
